					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><ul><li>PPU A10-13, /R, /W (6 pins) </li><li>CIRAM A10, /R, /CE (3 pins) </li></ul></div><br /><br />Technically, you don't need to send PPU /RD or /WR to the mapper - if you want CHR reads or writes to be blocked, then all you do is disable the ROM/RAM chip by pulling /CE high. Also, there is only one PPU /RD signal connected both to the cart edge and to VRAM (which you refer to as CIRAM for whatever reason, even though the NES board labels it as VRAM). VRAM /CE generally gets wired straight to PPU /A13 so as to always enable the nametables for PPU $2000-$3FFF unless you wanted to support ROM nametables.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Then 19 pins on the parts side:<br /><ul><li>CHR ROM A10-A18, /CE (10 pins) </li></ul>That makes a total of 44, which is (coincidentally?) the same number of pins as <a href="http://www.tripoint.org/kevtris/mappers/mmc3/" class="postlink">Kevin Horton's description of MMC3</a>. The MMC3 has one unused pin, which corresponds to CHR ROM A18 in this design.</div>
<br />
<br />Having lines for CHR A10-A18 would total to <strong>9</strong> bank select bits; the MMC3's CHR registers are only <strong>8</strong> bits wide...</div>

					
